"Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bruin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: from a personal name based on Middle Dutch <i>bruun</i> ‘brown’, or a nickname referring to the color of the hair or complexion. Compare   De Bruin   and   Bruyn  .","English: of uncertain origin. It may, as Reaney suggested, reflect a pronunciation of French   Brun   ‘brown’.","Altered form of Swiss <b>Bruhin</b>, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Brewin","meanings":["English (mainly Leicestershire): variant of   Bruin  .","Irish (Sligo): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Braoin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Braon</i>’, a byname meaning ‘moisture, drop’."]},{"name":"De Bruin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Maarten, Gerrit, Hendrik, Annick, Cornelis, Marinus.","Dutch: variant, with the definite article <i>de</i> ‘the’, of   Bruin   ‘brown’, a nickname referring to the color of the hair or complexion."]},{"name":"Bruins","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Albertus, Berend, Dirk, Gerrit.","Dutch: patronymic from   Bruin  ."]},{"name":"Bruinsma","meanings":["West Frisian: patronymic, formed with the suffix <i>-ma</i> ‘(one of the) men of’, from a genitivized form of the personal name   Bruin  ."]},{"name":"Bruyn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Dirk.","Dutch: variant of   Bruin  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William de Bruin was born in 1140, in Lusignan, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France, his father, Lord Walterus de Bruin de  Lusignan, was 35 and his mother, Agnes Brun, was 35. He married Lady Lucy Browne of Aberdeenshire in 1169, in Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1199, in Aberdeenshire, Scotland, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1140–1199":"1140–1199","1141–1191":"1141–1191","1169–1208":"1169–1208","1105–1199":"1105–1199","1105–1145":"1105–1145","1105":"1105","1169":"1169","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1199":"1199","1141":"1141","1140":"1140","1208":"1208","1191":"1191","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Lusignan, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Lusignan, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Aberdeen, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1140–1199":"1140–1199","1141–1191":"1141–1191","1169–1208":"1169–1208","1105–1199":"1105–1199","1105–1145":"1105–1145","1105":"1105","1169":"1169","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1199":"